                  <additions>
                    <list>
                        <item xml:id="e1">
                           <desc>
                              <locus target="#64r" facs="126">Fol. 64r</locus> The scribe possibly indicates the midpoint of the Psalms with a slight indent in the placement of the left margin for the midpoint line of text.
                        All other lines are carefully placed on the left justified margin</desc>
                        </item>
                        <item xml:id="e2">
                           <desc>Overlooked words of text are written interlinearly (<locus target="#24v #126r" facs="047 250">fols. 24v, 126r</locus>, )</desc>
                        </item>
                        <item xml:id="e3">
                           <desc>
                          The scribe regularly has to complete a line of text on another line. Much of the problem is addressed through the selection of an
                          appropriate aspect ratio for the codex combined with an appropriate script size. But, where the line of text is still too long, the scribe
                          completes the line of text above or below the end of the line (throughout). This scribe will also reduce the font size at the end of lines
                          to avoid having to go onto the next line (e.g., <locus target="#10v #26r #33v #35r #35v #36v" facs="019 050 065 068 069 071">fols. 10v, 26r, 33v, 35r, 35v, 36v</locus>, etc.)
                        </desc>
                        </item>

                        <item xml:id="e4">
